export const lessonRaw: Record<string, string> = {
  "programming-refresher/conditionals": "Real programs don't always run in a straight line — they need to make decisions. Conditionals let code choose a path based on the data.\n\n## `if` / `elif` / `else`\n\nA conditional runs a block only when a condition is `True`:\n\n```python\nscore = 72\n\nif score >= 60:\n    print(\"Pass\")\nelse:\n    print(\"Fail\")\n```\n\nNeed more than two outcomes? Chain with `elif` (\"else if\"):\n\n```python\nif score >= 90:\n    grade = \"A\"\nelif score >= 80:\n    grade = \"B\"\nelif score >= 70:\n    grade = \"C\"\nelse:\n    grade = \"F\"\n```\n\nPython checks top-to-bottom and runs **only the first branch that matches**, then skips the rest.\n\n## Conditions are just expressions\n\nEach condition is an expression that evaluates to a `bool`. Comparison and logical operators do the work:\n\n```python\nif age >= 18 and has_ticket:\n    print(\"Come in\")\n```\n\n## Truthiness\n\nIn a condition, Python treats some values as \"truthy\" or \"falsy\":\n\n- Falsy: `0`, `\"\"` (empty string), `[]` (empty list), `None`, `False`\n- Everything else is truthy.\n\n```python\nname = \"\"\n\nif name:                 # empty string is falsy\n    print(\"Hi\", name)\nelse:\n    print(\"No name given\")\n```\n\n> Indentation matters in Python. The lines under an `if` must be indented consistently — that's how Python knows what belongs to the branch.\n\nConditionals give your code branches; combined with variables and operators, you can already express a lot of logic. Next, we'll repeat work with loops.\n",
  "programming-refresher/functions": "As code grows, you'll write the same logic in many places. **Functions** let you package a block of code, give it a name, and reuse it. They're the main tool for keeping programs organised.\n\n## Defining and calling\n\nUse `def` to define a function, then call it by name:\n\n```python\ndef greet():\n    print(\"Hello!\")\n\ngreet()    # prints: Hello!\n```\n\n## Parameters and arguments\n\nA **parameter** is a placeholder in the definition; an **argument** is the actual value you pass in:\n\n```python\ndef greet(name):          # 'name' is a parameter\n    print(f\"Hello, {name}!\")\n\ngreet(\"Sajib\")            # \"Sajib\" is the argument\n```\n\nYou can have several, and give them **default values**:\n\n```python\ndef greet(name, excited=False):\n    ending = \"!\" if excited else \".\"\n    print(f\"Hello, {name}{ending}\")\n\ngreet(\"Sajib\")              # Hello, Sajib.\ngreet(\"Sajib\", excited=True)  # Hello, Sajib!\n```\n\n## Returning values\n\n`print` _shows_ a value; `return` _hands it back_ so the caller can use it. This distinction is crucial:\n\n```python\ndef add(a, b):\n    return a + b\n\nresult = add(2, 3)   # result is 5\n```\n\nA function without a `return` implicitly returns `None`.\n\n> A good function does **one thing** and returns a result. If you find a function printing _and_ calculating _and_ deciding, split it up. Small, focused functions are far easier to test and reuse.\n\n## Why bother?\n\nFunctions give you **abstraction** — once `add` works, you can use it without re-reading its body. They also make code testable: you can call `add(2, 3)` and check it returns `5`. When you learn recursion later, it's just a function that calls _itself_.\n\nFunctions are where code starts to become a system rather than a script. Next, we'll look at where their variables live.\n",
  "programming-refresher/how-programs-run": "Before we touch data structures or algorithms, it helps to understand what actually happens when you run a program. This lesson is a quick, practical refresher.\n\n## A program is a list of instructions\n\nWhen you run a Python program, the computer reads your code **line by line, top to bottom**, and does what each line says. That's it. Most of programming is just deciding the _order_ and the _conditions_ of those instructions.\n\n```python\nprint(\"Hello\")   # 1. say hello\nprint(\"World\")   # 2. say world\n```\n\nThese two lines run in order — `Hello`, then `World`. Order matters.\n\n## Statements vs expressions\n\nTwo words you'll see everywhere:\n\n- A **statement** is a complete instruction that _does_ something. `x = 5` is a statement.\n- An **expression** is anything that _evaluates to a value_. `5`, `2 + 3`, and `x * 2` are expressions.\n\nMost lines are a mix: `y = 2 + 3` is a statement (assign) built from an expression (`2 + 3`).\n\n```python\ntotal = 10 + 5   # '10 + 5' is an expression; the whole line is a statement\nprint(total)     # statement\n```\n\n## Comments and output\n\n- `print(...)` shows a value on the screen — your main way to _see_ what a program is doing.\n- Anything after `#` on a line is a **comment** — ignored by Python, meant for humans.\n\n> Use `print` liberally while learning. If you're not sure what a program is doing, print the values at each step and watch them appear.\n\nThat's the foundation: code runs in order, statements do things, expressions produce values. Everything else builds on this.\n",
  "programming-refresher/iteration-patterns": "Once you can loop, you'll start to notice the same shapes coming up again and again. These **iteration patterns** are the building blocks of most algorithms.\n\n## Counting\n\nCount how many items meet a condition:\n\n```python\nnumbers = [3, 7, 2, 9, 4]\ncount = 0\nfor n in numbers:\n    if n > 5:\n        count += 1\nprint(count)   # 2\n```\n\nThe pattern: start a counter at `0`, loop, add `1` when the condition holds.\n\n## Accumulating (sum, product)\n\nBuild up a running total:\n\n```python\ntotal = 0\nfor n in numbers:\n    total += n\nprint(total)   # 25\n```\n\nSame idea works for a running product — just start at `1` and multiply (`total *= n`).\n\n## Finding the max / min\n\nTrack the best value seen so far:\n\n```python\nbest = numbers[0]          # start with the first\nfor n in numbers:\n    if n > best:\n        best = n\nprint(best)   # 9\n```\n\n> Why start with `numbers[0]` instead of `0`? If every number is negative, starting at `0` would give the wrong max. Seeding with the first item is safer.\n\n## Building a new list\n\nCollect results into a new list as you go:\n\n```python\ndoubled = []\nfor n in numbers:\n    doubled.append(n * 2)\n# doubled = [6, 14, 4, 18, 8]\n```\n\nThis is the manual version of what Python's list comprehensions do:\n\n```python\ndoubled = [n * 2 for n in numbers]   # same result, shorter\n```\n\n## The big idea\n\nEvery one of these is \"loop + a variable that carries a result forward.\" Recognising the pattern — _count_, _accumulate_, _find best_, _collect_ — lets you read new algorithms quickly, because they're almost always combinations of these.\n",
  "programming-refresher/loops-iteration": "Loops are how a program repeats work without you writing the same line over and over. This is the heart of **iteration**, and almost every algorithm uses it.\n\n## `for` loops: repeat a known number of times\n\nA `for` loop walks through a sequence — most often a `range` of numbers or a collection:\n\n```python\nfor i in range(5):     # i = 0, 1, 2, 3, 4\n    print(i)\n```\n\n`range(5)` produces `0, 1, 2, 3, 4` (it stops _before_ 5). You can also loop directly over a list:\n\n```python\nfruits = [\"apple\", \"banana\", \"cherry\"]\nfor fruit in fruits:\n    print(fruit)\n```\n\n## `while` loops: repeat until something changes\n\nA `while` loop keeps going as long as its condition stays `True`:\n\n```python\ncount = 0\nwhile count < 3:\n    print(count)\n    count += 1        # don't forget to change the condition!\n```\n\n> A `while` loop whose condition never becomes `False` runs forever — an **infinite loop**. Always make sure something inside the loop moves toward stopping.\n\n## `break` and `continue`\n\n- `break` exits the loop immediately.\n- `continue` skips the rest of this round and moves to the next.\n\n```python\nfor n in range(10):\n    if n == 5:\n        break        # stop the whole loop\n    if n % 2 == 0:\n        continue     # skip even numbers\n    print(n)         # prints 1, 3\n```\n\n## Choosing between them\n\n- Use `for` when you know how many times to repeat (or you're walking a collection).\n- Use `while` when you repeat _until a condition changes_ (e.g. until a search finds what it wants).\n\nLoops turn \"do this once\" into \"do this many times\" — the exact tool algorithms need to scan, search, and transform data. The next lessons cover the common shapes loops take.\n",
  "programming-refresher/nested-loops": "Sometimes one loop isn't enough — you need to loop _inside_ a loop. **Nested loops** are how you handle grids, pairs, and multi-dimensional data.\n\n## A loop inside a loop\n\nFor every pass of the **outer** loop, the **inner** loop runs completely:\n\n```python\nfor i in range(3):        # outer\n    for j in range(3):    # inner — runs fully for each i\n        print(i, j)\n```\n\nThis prints:\n\n```text\n0 0\n0 1\n0 2\n1 0\n1 1\n1 2\n2 0\n2 1\n2 2\n```\n\nRead it as: \"for each row `i`, visit every column `j`.\"\n\n## The classic example: a times table\n\n```python\nfor i in range(1, 4):         # rows: 1, 2, 3\n    for j in range(1, 4):     # cols: 1, 2, 3\n        print(i * j, end=\" \")\n    print()                   # new line after each row\n```\n\n## Why this matters (and the cost)\n\nNested loops are natural for 2D structures — a grid of cells, all pairs of items, rows and columns of a matrix. But notice the cost: if the outer loop runs `n` times and the inner also runs `n` times, the body runs `n × n = n²` times.\n\n> This is your first taste of **quadratic** behaviour — `O(n²)`. It's fine for small inputs but gets slow fast as `n` grows. Many algorithm problems are really about _avoiding_ a nested loop when you can.\n\n## When do you actually need one?\n\n- Iterating over a 2D list / matrix.\n- Comparing every item with every other item (all pairs).\n- Generating combinations.\n\nIf you ever write two nested loops, pause and ask: \"do I really need to look at every pair, or is there a smarter way?\" That instinct is exactly what later phases (like the two-pointers and sliding-window patterns) sharpen.\n",
  "programming-refresher/scope-tracing": "\"Scope\" is the rule for _where a variable exists_. Get this straight now and you'll dodge a huge class of bugs — and it sets up the call-stack mental model you'll need for recursion.\n\n## Local vs global\n\nA variable created **inside** a function is **local** — it only exists there:\n\n```python\ndef do_something():\n    message = \"hi\"     # local to this function\n    print(message)\n\ndo_something()         # prints: hi\nprint(message)         # NameError — message doesn't exist out here\n```\n\nA variable created **outside** all functions is **global** — any function can read it:\n\n```python\ncounter = 0            # global\n\ndef show():\n    print(counter)     # reading a global is fine\n\nshow()                 # 0\n```\n\nBut assigning inside a function creates a _new local_ unless you say otherwise — a common trap:\n\n```python\ncounter = 0\n\ndef bump():\n    counter = counter + 1   # UnboundLocalError!\n\nbump()\n```\n\n> If a function only needs to _read_ a global, that's fine. If it needs to _change_ it, prefer passing the value in and returning the new one — much clearer than `global`.\n\n```python\ndef bump(counter):\n    return counter + 1\n\ncounter = bump(counter)   # explicit, no surprises\n```\n\n## Tracing code by hand\n\nThe single best debugging skill: **trace** the code line by line, tracking each variable's value. Take this:\n\n```python\nx = 1\nfor i in range(3):\n    x = x + i\nprint(x)\n```\n\nTrace it:\n\n| step    | `i` | `x` |\n| ------- | --- | --- |\n| start   | –   | 1   |\n| round 1 | 0   | 1   |\n| round 2 | 1   | 2   |\n| round 3 | 2   | 4   |\n\nSo it prints `4`.\n\n## Why this matters for DSA\n\nWhen you learn recursion, the **call stack** is just a stack of these local scopes — each call gets its own fresh copies of its variables, and they disappear when the call returns. Tracing a few loops by hand now trains exactly the muscle you'll use to trace a recursive function later.\n\nIf a piece of code confuses you, slow down and trace it. A pencil and a small table beat staring at the screen every time.\n",
  "programming-refresher/variables-types": "To do useful work, a program has to _remember_ things. That's what variables are for.\n\n## Variables are labelled boxes\n\nA **variable** is a name you give to a value so you can reuse it later. You create one with assignment (`=`):\n\n```python\nage = 25\nname = \"Sajib\"\nis_ready = True\n```\n\nRead `age = 25` as \"put `25` into the box labelled `age`\". You can change what's in the box anytime:\n\n```python\nscore = 0\nscore = score + 10   # score is now 10\nscore += 5           # shortcut: score is now 15\n```\n\n## Common types\n\nEvery value has a **type**. Python figures out the type automatically (it's _dynamically typed_):\n\n| Type    | Example          | Meaning               |\n| ------- | ---------------- | --------------------- |\n| `int`   | `42`             | whole numbers         |\n| `float` | `3.14`           | decimal numbers       |\n| `str`   | `\"hello\"`        | text                  |\n| `bool`  | `True` / `False` | truth values          |\n| `list`  | `[1, 2, 3]`      | an ordered collection |\n\nYou can check a value's type with `type(...)`:\n\n```python\ntype(42)        # <class 'int'>\ntype(\"hello\")   # <class 'str'>\n```\n\n## Operators\n\nOperators combine values into expressions. The ones you'll use constantly:\n\n- **Arithmetic:** `+  -  *  /  //  %  **`\n- **Comparison:** `==  !=  <  >  <=  >=` (these produce `bool`)\n- **Logical:** `and`, `or`, `not`\n\n```python\n5 + 2     # 7\n10 % 3    # 1  (remainder)\n5 > 3     # True\nnot True  # False\n```\n\n> Watch out for `=` vs `==`. A single `=` _assigns_ a value; a double `==` _compares_ two values.\n\nYou now have the building blocks: named values, types, and operators. Next we'll use them to make decisions.\n",
};
